##"REVENGE SPENDING? I PREFER REVENGE MONEY! "

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

-- Wang Fengjiao, Huang Yulu

People "war epidemic" has been three months, people "home" has been months, the epidemic almost all entertainment stopped, but did not stop to think "wave" heart.

As the epidemic situation gradually stabilized, a large area of the country back to work, on the "retaliatory consumption" discussion and sound higher and higher. The 360 trend shows that the term "retaliatory consumption" has fluctuated significantly since the beginning of February, even peaking on March 5.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At the same time, consumer's shopping, travel desire gradually appears. Recently, I saw in Changping District, Beijing, a northwest restaurant entrance, although disinfection, separate seating requirements are strict, but does not prevent seven or eight people in the cold Beijing outdoor queue for meals. Media reports, Hangzhou Tower Shopping Mall resumed business, five-hour sales exceeded 11 million yuan, Beijing Fragrance Hill scenic area hit a traffic jam search, Luoyang Sui Tang city botanical garden on March 8 more than 50,000 visitors a day to admire flowers..

So will there really be a wave of "retaliatory consumption" after the epidemic? What consumption habits will the epidemic change? Online shopping will continue to increase the impact of the offline channel? The world is so big, where do the Chinese want to "Surf" ?

Recently, nearly 1,000 people answered the question of whether or not they would like to spend after a pandemic

Online shopping is convenient, but most of the respondents still miss "market fireworks" and "Busy Shopping Malls" ; more people want to build up their bodies and fight the virus after an epidemic than they want to eat and drink and get fat; and more people want to fight the virus than "revenge consumption" and "going around the world" , trying to earn and save money is the way to go.

Fresh e-commerce boom, perhaps just a fireworks

As you can see, the outbreak has triggered a lot of new consumption habits, for example, the elderly began to learn to buy food online, enjoy the convenience of life brought by the Internet.

Li Hua, 48, who lives in Beijing, used to be a regular at supermarkets and vegetable farms, but she learned to shop online for vegetables when she was not proficient in smartphone use at the time of the epidemic, "It's so convenient to get home safely and on time with just a touch of your finger! "

Not only did sister Li benefit. During the Spring Festival, the daily turnover from the Spring Festival eve to the fourth day of the Lunar New Year increased by 321% compared with the same period last year, while orders for the Dingdong shopping festival rose by more than 300% compared with the previous month, the average daily order volume of Meituan shopping in Beijing is 2-3 times that before the festival, and the online order volume of Hema fresh food in Guangzhou, Shenzhen and Chengdu is 5-10 times that in normal times.

It seems that e-commerce platforms such as fresh and send-as-you-go are the "winners" , but only 31 per cent of respondents said they would continue to buy online after the outbreak ended, while 69 per cent said they would prefer to go out and buy food and household items. "Why not go for a walk and exercise while you can pick your favorite vegetables? " Chun Afong, who is about Li's age, told me.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
So, if the end of the epidemic, fresh E-COMMERCE "mass base" is likely to be shaken?

"This outbreak only left a window period for the fresh e-commerce market, " said Sun Mengzi, deputy general manager and senior analyst of analysys group, is Fresh E-commerce "low-cost customers and the loss of the old user back window, " but want to keep going, still need to "test the enterprise" , at the same time, fresh e-commerce demand should be "depending on where" .

Sun Mengzi analyzed that the pace of life in the first-and second-tier cities is relatively fast, and the demand for food distribution or high-end distribution is likely to continue after the epidemic is over, even some of the first-tier cities to provide the elderly online shopping habits and a more clear direction, "people always have legs uncomfortable, online is to give them a new choice. ". But below the third-tier cities are not the main market covered by fresh e-commerce, during the epidemic, fresh distribution is only a short-term relief for residents, long-term demand will decline.

In the future, according to Sun Mengzi, the type of content or service offered by fresh e-commerce will change. If you want to retain users, standardize your products, diversify your categories, control your supply chain, and draw a clear picture of your users, etc. , "It's all about testing the inner strength of the business, " said mintel retail research analyst Shi Yang. "To a large extent, the epidemic has actually accelerated the integration of online and offline, " as well as the development of a multi-channel approach to fresh retail, in the long run, fresh produce retailing will continue to grow.

And looking at the broader consumer scene and category, mintel luxury and fashion retail research analyst Xia Yue believes that entertainment consumption and a more complete consumer experience will eventually become the way to survive for offline channels. For some categories, for example, for high-end products and luxury goods, offline channels are an indispensable part, because online channels carry more tasks of spreading brand information, and consumers with high unit prices still tend to do it offline, "after the epidemic stabilizes, the offline experience consumption and entertainment catering will gradually pick up, will not change because of the epidemic" .

It seems that whether it is fresh or other categories, online shopping is indeed the general trend, but offline "shopping" pleasure, still can not be easily replaced.

"I'd rather die than eat. "

After the outbreak, if the offline experience and entertainment consumption will pick up, consumers will choose which items?

In the "one thing we'd like to do after a pandemic" poll, we found that 15 per cent of respondents chose fitness as their second most popular activity, ahead of shopping, travel, movies, gourmet food and Karaoke.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
After 90, Qin Dong once was a real Otaku man, "home from work to eat takeout, play games, stay up until midnight. ". However, this outbreak has made a big change in his mind, "I was surprised how much money I could save by cooking, " she said. "In this outbreak, the symptoms of infected people with weakened immune systems will be severe, so I will pay more attention to fitness, diet and healthy living. ".

The survey data and the shift in Qin Dong more or less reflect the impact of the epidemic on Chinese People's health perceptions, said Liu Wenshi, a research analyst at mintel, the epidemic has given rise to the concept of "overall health" consumption through multi-dimensional promotion.

"since there is no specific drug that can really boost the immune system, people can maintain good immune status through a variety of means, such as a balanced diet, more exercise, supplements, health counselling and regulating mood, " Liu explained, meanwhile, according to MINTEL's 2019 global consumer survey of 35 markets, 90% of Chinese consumers believe that emotional health management is important to them, the outbreak has also made many consumers realize that physical and mental health are equally important.

The change in health philosophy triggered by the outbreak may also lead to new health products, consumer experiences and even business opportunities.

Some health care brands are attracting consumers to buy their products by matching them with online sports tutorials and nutrition advice, Liu said. During the epidemic, long-distance psychological counseling services appeared frequently, it also offers a potential direction for how the health care industry can be more proactive in helping consumers improve their emotional health.

Moreover, according to Liu Wenshi, the epidemic has made the public aware of the potential threat of animal transmission of the virus, in addition to taking more health and epidemic prevention measures and establishing stricter trade regulations, it also forces people to rethink their eating habits, "For example, whether safer and more sustainable sources of protein should be sought is likely to boost the market prospects for plant-based meat products or artificial meat in China. ".

Perhaps we can imagine a scenario in which you're sweating it out at the gym one day after the outbreak ends, and your physical signs are being synchronized into the health products industry's data backend, there will be a dedicated health analyst who will match you with meals and supplements, a psychologist who will listen to your worries and soothe your mind remotely, and at mealtime, you will no longer be chewing streaky, tendinous meat, it's artificial meat made from plant extracts or cells.

Don't want revenge spending, just revenge money

The outbreak has spurred a shift in consumer attitudes that could lead to entirely new consumption scenarios, but it has delayed work for so long that it has left many people confused about what to play with and what to consume.

One result of the poll, "post-epidemic consumption concept, " showed that 51 percent of the respondents' consumption concept after the epidemic was to work harder and earn more money, and 41 percent of the respondents even said they would save money to cope with unknown risks, only 8% of the respondents chose to have a good time and spend like crazy.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the "one thing I'd like to do after an outbreak" poll mentioned above, we can also see that the top choice is "make money. ". Of the 5,564 people who took part in the Weibo poll of "where do you want to travel after the epidemic is over? " 2,607 chose "house habit, only want to work. " The number of people who chose to travel was the highest, even surpassing "to see the beautiful country of China. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Even if they plan to travel after the outbreak, 52 percent of the respondents said they planned to travel within 5,000 yuan, and 27 percent said they planned to travel between 5,000 yuan and 10,000 yuan. Staying within our means seems to be the choice most consumers make after the epidemic is over.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Poverty was almost a common refrain among many stay-at-home families during the outbreak:

"We've cut our income in half. We're lucky if we don't eat dirt. When we go out, we have to drink the wind. "

"half-dead business, work can not pay, this period of time to eat a lot of capital, take what crazy, live on the line. "

A netizen who has not started work said to the author: "I used to think moonlight is nothing, but now performance is not issued during the epidemic, there is no guarantee of income, rent day still comes on time, with what consumption? Or work hard. "

So will the much-discussed "retaliatory spending" really happen on a large scale?

Before discussing whether there will be "retaliatory consumption" , Sun Mengzi believes that the first step is to define what "retaliatory consumption" is. In her view, the so-called "retaliatory consumption" , refers to the epidemic after the consumer demand has been more intensive, and people May "buy pure and buy, pure and spend" , that is, consumers will buy the original demand is not big, can not have a key impact on real life, not only limited to high-end luxury goods, but also may be "small, intensive frequency" of products and experiences. From this definition and previous research, Sun Mengzi predicted that after the end of the epidemic may have a similar "retaliatory consumption. ".

But from the perspective of consumer psychology, Sun Mengzi said that before the outbreak, many people were unable to perceive the impact of particularly significant social events on everyone, even at the level of life and survival, and that the epidemic was actually a wake-up call, "This time it really affected your pocketbooks. ". In fact, starting in 2019, due to the downward pressure on the economy, "some people's hands have started to tighten inside. ".

Therefore, judging from the results of the vote, more people are likely to add various kinds of financial security to themselves at the investment level in the future. In the long run, consumers will be more "rational and rational" as their consumption concept is still mainly tightened, a preference for "conservative consumption" does not mean a "downgrading of consumption" .

In the words of Sun Mengzi, "rational consumption will come first" and "making money is eternal" after the epidemic is over.

So the question is: What would you choose between "retaliatory spending" and "retaliatory saving" ?
